{"title_page": "Fangyi (vessel)", "text_new": "[[File:Fang yi vessel, Shang (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|Fangyi dated to the 12th century BCE (Shang dynasty)]]\nA '''''fangyi''''' ({{zh|s=\u65b9\u5f5c|w=fang-i}}; 'square bronze') is a type of [[Chinese ritual bronzes|Chinese ritual bronze]] container typical of the [[Shang dynasty|Shang]] and early to middle [[Zhou dynasty|Zhou]] periods of [[Bronze_Age#China|Bronze Age China]] (circa 1800-900 BCE). It takes the shape of a square or rectangular casket with a cover that resembles a [[hip roof]], surmounted by a knob of a similar hipped appearance. The lower edge is typically indented with a semi-circular notch.<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/fangyi|title=Fangyi|work=Britannica.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey are usually lavishly decorated, often with ''[[taotie]]'' patterns representing mythological beasts. They were sometimes connected to create a twin container or ''oufangyi''. Their form differed somewhat over time; those produced during the Shang typically had straight bodies, those of the early Zhou bulge at the sides and mid-Zhou ones have handles that look like an elephant's trunk.<ref name=\"Britannica\" /> The Sinologist Carl Hentze suggested that the shape of the vessel represents an ancestral temple of the period, with sloping roofs, projecting beams and a square or rectangular base.<ref>{{cite book|title=Arts of China|last=Munsterberg|first=Hugo|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|date=2011}}</ref>\n\n''Fangyi'' appear to have evolved from pottery vessels in the [[Neolithic China|Neolithic period]] and were also carved from white marble during the Shang. They first appeared in bronze either at the start of the [[Yinxu]] period (13th-11th century BC) or during the 14th century transition between the [[Erligang culture]] and the Yinxu. They disappeared in the middle part of the Western Zhou period.<ref>{{cite book|title=Understanding Ancient Chinese Bronzes, Their Importance in Chinese Culture, Their Shapes, Functions and Motifs|last=Dedier|first=Christian|page=37|isbn=9782955416006|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThey are believed to have been used to hold ritual food offerings, though it is also possible that they could have been used to hold wine.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Penguin Dictionary of Decorative Arts|publisher=Viking|author1-last=Fleming|author1-first=John|author2-last=Honour|author2-first=Hugh|date=1979|page=300|isbn=0670820474}}</ref> During the Shang and Zhou eras, kings and aristocrats customarily sought to bring good fortune and avert evil by sacrificing to the ancestors. They were used both in life and as [[grave good]]s, and have been found in tombs such as that of the 13th century BC queen [[Tomb of Fu Hao|Fu Hao]].<ref name=\"KhanAcademy\">{{cite web|title=Ritual vessel (fangyi)|url=https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/asian-art-museum/aam-china-topic/aam-china/a/ritual-vessel-fangyi|publisher=Khan Academy|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany ''fangyi'' were inscribed with very early forms of [[Chinese writing]], generally representing the names of the owners of the vessels or the ancestors to whom they were dedicated. The inscriptions usually appear on the interior walls or floors of the vessels and on the undersides of the lids. They were cast into the bronze rather than being incised into the metal. The highly pictographic form of the shorter Shang-era inscriptions later developed into lengthier inscriptions by the time of the Zhou, with more standardised written characters often commemorating events involving the individual who had commissioned the vessel. ''Fangyi'' thus represent an important source for ancient Chinese history and the development of the Chinese writing system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/art/203988|title='Fangyi' Covered Ritual Wine Vessel with 'Taotie' Decor|publisher=Harvard Art Museums|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{commonscat|Fangyi (vessel)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://3d.si.edu/object/3d/square-lidded-ritual-wine-container-fangyi-taotie-serpents-and-birds%3Ad8c62f94-4ebc-11ea-b77f-2e728ce88125 3D model of a ''fangyi'' (Smithsonian Institution)]\n\n{{Chinese bronzeware}}\n\n[[Category:Bronze Age art]]\n[[Category:Chinese art|Bronzes]]\n[[Category:Chinese bronzeware|*]]\n[[Category:Containers|*]]\n[[Category:Visual arts terminology]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fang yi vessel, Shang (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|Fangyi dated to the 12th century BCE (Shang dynasty)]]\nA '''''fangyi''''' ({{zh|s=\u65b9\u5f5c|w=fang-i}}; 'square bronze') is a type of [[Chinese ritual bronzes|Chinese ritual bronze]] container typical of the [[Shang dynasty|Shang]] and early to middle [[Zhou dynasty|Zhou]] periods of [[Bronze_Age#China|Bronze Age China]] (circa 1800-900 BCE). It takes the shape of a square or rectangular casket with a cover that resembles a [[hip roof]], surmounted by a knob of a similar hipped appearance. The lower edge is typically indented with a semi-circular notch.<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/fangyi|title=Fangyi|work=Britannica.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey are usually lavishly decorated, often with ''[[taotie]]'' patterns representing mythological beasts. They were sometimes connected to create a twin container or ''oufangyi''. Their form differed somewhat over time; those produced during the Shang typically had straight bodies, those of the early Zhou bulge at the sides and mid-Zhou ones have handles that look like an elephant's trunk.<ref name=\"Britannica\" /> The Sinologist Carl Hentze] suggested that the shape of the vessel represents an ancestral temple of the period, with sloping roofs, projecting beams and a square or rectangular base.<ref>{{cite book|title=Arts of China|last=Munsterberg|first=Hugo|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|date=2011}}</ref>\n\n''Fangyi'' appear to have evolved from pottery vessels in the [[Neolithic China|Neolithic period]] and were also carved from white marble during the Shang. They first appeared in bronze either at the start of the [[Yinxu]] period (13th-11th century BC) or during the 14th century transition between the [[Erligang culture]] and the Yinxu. They disappeared in the middle part of the Western Zhou period.<ref>{{cite book|title=Understanding Ancient Chinese Bronzes, Their Importance in Chinese Culture, Their Shapes, Functions and Motifs|last=Dedier|first=Christian|page=37|isbn=9782955416006|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThey are believed to have been used to hold ritual food offerings, though it is also possible that they could have been used to hold wine.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Penguin Dictionary of Decorative Arts|publisher=Viking|author1-last=Fleming|author1-first=John|author2-last=Honour|author2-first=Hugh|date=1979|page=300|isbn=0670820474}}</ref> During the Shang and Zhou eras, kings and aristocrats customarily sought to bring good fortune and avert evil by sacrificing to the ancestors. They were used both in life and as [[grave good]]s, and have been found in tombs such as that of the 13th century BC queen [[Tomb of Fu Hao|Fu Hao]].<ref name=\"KhanAcademy\">{{cite web|title=Ritual vessel (fangyi)|url=https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/asian-art-museum/aam-china-topic/aam-china/a/ritual-vessel-fangyi|publisher=Khan Academy|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany ''fangyi'' were inscribed with very early forms of [[Chinese writing]], generally representing the names of the owners of the vessels or the ancestors to whom they were dedicated. The inscriptions usually appear on the interior walls or floors of the vessels and on the undersides of the lids. They were cast into the bronze rather than being incised into the metal. The highly pictographic form of the shorter Shang-era inscriptions later developed into lengthier inscriptions by the time of the Zhou, with more standardised written characters often commemorating events involving the individual who had commissioned the vessel. ''Fangyi'' thus represent an important source for ancient Chinese history and the development of the Chinese writing system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/art/203988|title='Fangyi' Covered Ritual Wine Vessel with 'Taotie' Decor|publisher=Harvard Art Museums|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{commonscat|Fangyi (vessel)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://3d.si.edu/object/3d/square-lidded-ritual-wine-container-fangyi-taotie-serpents-and-birds%3Ad8c62f94-4ebc-11ea-b77f-2e728ce88125 3D model of a ''fangyi'' (Smithsonian Institution)]\n\n{{Chinese bronzeware}}\n\n[[Category:Bronze Age art]]\n[[Category:Chinese art|Bronzes]]\n[[Category:Chinese bronzeware|*]]\n[[Category:Containers|*]]\n[[Category:Visual arts terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Prioryman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fangyi_(vessel)"}
{"title_page": "Bonnie Bo", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=December 2011}}\n{{orphan|date=March 2012}}\n{{no footnotes|date=December 2011}}\n}}\n\n'''Bonnie Bo''' (also can be read as Bonnie Bai; traditional Chinese: \u67cf\u90a6\u59ae; simplified Chinese: \u67cf\u90a6\u59ae; form name: \u5f20\u73ca\u73ca) was born on 1982. She is an [[author]] and [[screenwriter]]. Bonnie graduated in Literature and reading from [[Beijing Film Academy]]. In 2005 she published a personal collection of essays known as \"The Same As Bonnie Love You.\" Bo writes for fashion magazine, [[Interview (magazine)|Interview]], and worked as a film critic and columnist from 2003. She interviewed [[Maggie Cheung]], [[Gong Li]], [[Ang Lee]], [[Hou Hsiao-hsien]] and other celebrities. She worked as a [[screenwriter]] for the TV shows ''Yan Qing prodigal son'', ''Flea on the drum when the move'' and ''Than I love my''. She wrote the screenplay for the movie ''Ballad of loess'' and part of the 2008 remake of ''Dream of Red Mansions''.\n\n==Early life==\nBonnie's parents worked in [[research institute]]s. Once, her mother had a high fever and her father wanted to take her to the hospital. Bonnie's mom responded: \"I did not put on make-up, I will not go out!\" Bo later recalled, \"Mother, who was insistent on makeup, simply shows a great attitude to life: a woman, no matter when, has to be beautiful and proud to face life, to be able to lift her head high.\"\n\nBonnie was the champion of her province's art examination and was admitted to Nanjing Arts Institute. After a year, she became interested in [[film]], leading her to become the first dropout in the school's history. In 2002, she entered Beijing Film Academy and spent four years there.\n\n==Career==\nIn March 2008, Bo joined a group of eight other writers to script a remake of \"Dream of Red Mansions\". Three months later, the \"youthful dream team\" had finished 50 drafts. Bonnie was responsible for eight scenes.\n\n==Filmography==\n*\"Flea on the drum when the move\" (screenwriter)\n*\"Prodigal Yan Qing\" (screenwriter)\n*\"Loess Ballad\" (screenwriter)\n*New version of \"Dream of Red Mansions\" (writer)\n*The movie \"Mulan\" (screenwriter)\n*\"Like love you like Bonnie 'essays\n*\"Not luxury\", \"false\" celebrity interviews set\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/1552981.htm |title=\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae_\u767e\u5ea6\u767e\u79d1 |publisher=Baike.baidu.com |date=2012-02-24 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://women.sohu.com/20080702/n257880570_4.shtml |title=\u72ec\u5bb6\u91c7\u8bbf\uff1a\u5486\u54ee\u5973\u90ce\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae-\u641c\u72d0\u5973\u4eba |publisher=Women.sohu.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.kaixin001.com/diary/view_65218987_29840495.html |title=\u65b0\u7248\u300a\u7ea2\u697c\u68a6\u300b\u4e3b\u529b\u7f16\u5267\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae:\u9000\u5b66\u7684\u9ad8\u8003\u72b6\u5143 - \u300a\u610f\u6797\u300b\u7684\u65e5\u8bb0 - \u5f00\u5fc3\u7f51 |publisher=Kaixin001.com |date=2010-03-26 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.tianshannet.com.cn/special/banlv/200907/2009-07/30/content_4364987.htm |title=\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae\uff1a\u50cf38D\u4e00\u6837\u9a84\u50b2\u5730\u751f\u6d3b - \u65b0\u7586\u5929\u5c71\u7f51 |publisher=[[Tianshannet]].com.cn |date=2009-07-30 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|author=\u8ddf\u8d34\u533a |url=http://news.163.com/10/0723/09/6C93COF900014AEE.html |title=\u7f16\u5267\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae\uff1a\u5174\u9ad8\u91c7\u70c8\u5954\u8dd1\u7684\u516b\u5341\u540e(\u56fe)_\u7f51\u6613\u65b0\u95fb\u4e2d\u5fc3 |publisher=News.163.com |date=2010-05-29 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://product.dangdang.com/product.aspx?product_id=20620809 |title=\u4e0d\u534e - \u56fe\u4e66 - \u5f53\u5f53\u7f51 |publisher=Product.dangdang.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-29}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://bulaoge.net/?bonnie |title=\u5486\u54ee\u5973\u90ce\u67cf\u90a6\u59ae @ \u4e